1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1195":"1195","about 1166":"circa 1166","Elland, Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1110–1166":"1110–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Deceased","1166–Female":"1166–Deceased","–1195":"–1195","1115":"1115","1133":"1133","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1195":"1195","about 1166":"about 1166","Elland, Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Eland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Elland (Yorkshire) or Little Eland (Northumberland), both of which derive their names from Old English <i>ēaland</i> ‘cultivated land by water or a river’.","Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>adel</i> ‘noble’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh de Eland was born in 1110, in Elland, Yorkshire, England. He married Mrs. Hugh de Eland in 1133, in Elland, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1166, in his hometown, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1110–1166":"1110–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","1166–Female":"1166–Surnud","–1195":"–1195","1115":"1115","1133":"1133","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1195":"1195","about 1166":"umbes 1166","Elland, Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1110–1166":"1110–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Kuollut","1166–Female":"1166–Kuollut","–1195":"–1195","1115":"1115","1133":"1133","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1195":"1195","about 1166":"noin 1166","Elland, Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1110–1166":"1110–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Décédée","1166–Female":"1166–Décédée","–1195":"–1195","1115":"1115","1133":"1133","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1195":"1195","about 1166":"environ 1166","Elland, Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Hugh d’Eland est né en 1110, à Elland, Everwyck, Angleterre. Il a épousé Mrs. Hugh d’Eland en 1133, à Elland, Everwyck, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1166, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 56 ans."},"de":{"1110–1166":"1110–1166","1115–Female":"1115–Verstorben","1166–Female":"1166–Verstorben","–1195":"–1195","1115":"1115","1133":"1133","1166":"1166","1110":"1110","1195":"1195","about 1166":"um 1166","Elland, Yorkshire, England":"Elland, Yorkshire, E